answers.explanation:
The inferior macular vulnerability zone (MVZ), which was first described by Hood et al. in 2013, is a key region affected in glaucoma. The inferior MVZ, which is located largely in the inferiotemporal quadrant of the optic disc, is highly susceptible to glaucomatous damage. This inferotemporal quadrant receives RNFL fibres from the inferior macula, which leads to the classic superior arcuate visual field deficits in glaucoma.

​References;

Hood DC, Raza AS, de Moraes CG, Liebmann JM, Ritch R. Glaucomatous damage of the macula. Prog Retin Eye Res 2013;32:1-21.
